e feedback effect from human development to corruption. Figure 3.3 plots the CCI 2007 against the HDI 2005; that is HDI for a previous year with the CCI for a later year. This figure also shows that countries that have higher (better) control of cor- ruption also have high human devel- opment, as is the case with Malaysia, Japan, Singapore and Australia. On the other hand, Bangladesh, Timor-Leste, Papua New Guinea have lower con- trol of corruption and lower attain- ment of human development. Bhutan 13 16 Plotting CCI 2006 with HDI 1980 to allow for the effect of initial levels of human development also rein forces the same pattern. Note: The green line marks countries between low and medium human development; the black line marks countries between medium and high human development. Source: World Bank 2008; UNDP 2007. Figure 3.2: Control of corruption and human development Figure 3.3: Human development and control of corruption 0.20 0.30 0.40 0.50 0.60 0.70 0.80 0.90 1.00 2.50 2.00 1.50 1.00 0.50 0.00 -0.50 -1.00 -1.50 -2.00 -2.50 Control of corruption index 2007 Human Development index 2005 Cambodia Myanmar Bangladesh Nepal India China Hong kong, China (SAR) Brunei Darussalam Newzealand Australia Samoa Island Indonesia Papua New Guinea Philippines Bhutan Thailand Sri Lanka Malaysia Japan Note: The green line marks countries between low and medium human development; the black line marks countries between medium and high human development. Source: World Bank 2008; UNDP 2007. is an outlier; it has a higher corrup- tion control but relatively low human development. The pattern thus seems to suggest that human development conditions and corruption control move together. While correlation is not causation, it is probable that causality may run from human development to corruption while acknowledging that, simultaneously, high corruption con- trol may positively influence human development.16 0.20 0.30 0.40 0.50 0.60 0.70 0.80 0.90 1.00 2.50 2.00 1.50 1.00 0.50 0.00 -0.50